article.headline: Minnesota 74, UCF 63
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota players wanted to enter a 10-day break and final exams with a good feeling. They will. Dan Coleman and Spencer Tollackson had double-doubles to lead the Gophers past Central Florida 74-63 on Tuesday. Coleman scored a career-high 29 points and added 10 rebounds for his first career double-digit effort in each category. Tollackson had 13 points and 11 rebounds for his third career double-double. "It's momentum because we have a little bit of a break, and you don't want to have a bad taste going into a road game, especially at UNLV," said Coleman, whose team is scheduled to play the Running Rebels on Dec. 22. "This was big because it makes people feel a little bit better, and you don't want to go out on a couple-game losing streak." Jamal Abu-Shamala and Lawrence McKenzie scored nine points each for Minnesota (5-7), which won for just the third time in 10 games. Jermaine Taylor led the Golden Knights (6-1) with 22 points off the bench. Dave Noel had 15 points for Central Florida, which averaged 84 points per game in its previous outings. In rebounding, Minnesota had a 42-30 edge against UCF, after being beaten 43-16 on the boards in Saturday's loss to Arkansas-Little Rock. "Players don't really learn what you teach, they learn what you emphasize," said interim coach Jim Molinari. "We emphasized rebounding and they took on the challenge. I thought we blocked out better and our guards were in there trying to rebound." Minnesota's starting backcourt of McKenzie and Limar Wilson had six rebounds each. The physical Gophers came out more aggressive on the glass against the Golden Knights. Just 30 seconds into the game, Tollackson beat two UCF players on two of his own misses to start a 3-point play. "Getting offensive rebounds are energy plays and we fed off those today," said Abu-Shamala. Minnesota had eight rebounds in less than four minutes, 17 rebounds at the 7:19 mark, and 25 boards in the first half -- nine of them offensive. "I knew that they'd come out with great energy on the boards and they did a great job on the boards tonight and really took it to us," said UCF coach Kirk Speraw. "They're an improving basketball team." Minnesota led 36-21 at the half. A pair of free throws by Taylor, the Golden Knights leading scorer in five of seven games, got UCF within 10 early in the second half, but a 3-pointer from Abu-Shamala and a jumper by Coleman gave Minnesota a 43-28 lead. Abu-Shamala scored his points on three 3-pointers, matching his total from the previous five games combined. "I just said to myself, "If I get an open look I'm going to shoot it,' and try to get some confidence back," he said. "After I hit the first one I felt a lot more comfortable out there." UCF got within 54-46 on a 3-pointer by Josh Peppers with 7:02 to play, but Minnesota responded with a 9-0 run -- including seven points by Coleman -- to put the game away. Coleman finished 10-of-12 from the free-throw line, but his teammates were a combined 6-for-17, including 3-for-9 from Tollackson. Still, Molinari won't let that blemish temper his overall pleasure. "We've had 10 games in 22 days, so I'm extremely proud of our team. We could've finished it better, but after playing that many games we really hung in there and held off."
